payload.user_prompt:
Propose 3 distinct strategies to beat the baseline.

PROBLEM: Euclidean Travelling Salesman Problem: given N cities as (x, y) points, find the shortest closed tour visiting every city exactly once. Score = total tour length (lower is better).
INSTANCE: 60 cities, uniform random in [0,1000]^2, seed=42
SCOPE: {"objective": "Minimize the total Euclidean tour length for a 60-city TSP instance (seed=42) below the nearest-neighbor baseline of 7489.18 by applying metaheuristic or exact-approximation methods within budget and time constraints.", "success_criteria": {"target_improvement_pct": 18.0, "rationale": "The operator suggests 18% improvement, yielding a target tour length of ~6141.1. For 60 cities, well-implemented 2-opt or 3-opt local search typically achieves 15-25% improvement over nearest-neighbor, and Or-opt/LKH-style moves can reach near-optimal solutions. An 18% target is ambitious but achievable within 10s per experiment for this instance size, as 60 cities is small enough for thorough local search."}, "constraints": ["Maximum 5 optimization rounds total", "Budget cap of $2 USD across all LLM/API calls", "Each experiment must complete within 10 seconds wall-clock time", "Tour must be a valid Hamiltonian cycle: visit all 60 cities exactly once and return to start", "Only Euclidean distances between given (x,y) coordinates are used for scoring", "No external TSP solver binaries (e.g., Concorde) unless already available in the environment"], "stop_conditions": ["Tour length reaches or falls below 6141.1 (18% improvement over baseline)", "All 5 rounds are exhausted", "Budget of $2 USD is consumed", "No improvement greater than 0.5% is observed between consecutive rounds, suggesting convergence"], "reasoning": "For 60 cities, nearest-neighbor is a weak heuristic that typically produces tours 20-25% above optimal. The optimal for a 60-city uniform random instance is usually reachable via LKH or branch-and-bound, but within 10s we rely on local search. 2-opt alone on 60 cities runs in milliseconds and commonly achieves 10-15% improvement; adding 3-opt or Lin-Kernighan moves pushes toward 18-22%. The 18% target aligns with what a well-implemented 2-opt + or-opt hybrid can reliably achieve, making it challenging but realistic within the given constraints. Five rounds provide enough iterations to progressively refine the algorithm (e.g., start with 2-opt, add 3-opt, tune restarts with random perturbation)."}

Each strategy must be implementable in pure Python within the time limit.
Return JSON:
{
  "hypotheses": [
    {"name": "<short name>", "strategy": "<algorithm family>",
      "hypothesis": "<falsifiable claim: doing X will improve over baseline because Y>",
      "risk": "<main reason this could fail>"}
  ]
}

